msgid "Managing versions"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:50
msgid "To set the default toolchain to something other than `stable`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:56
msgid ""
"To uninstall a specific Rust version, you can use `rustup toolchain "
"uninstall`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:62
msgid "To use a toolchain other than the default, use `rustup run`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:68
msgid "There's also an alias for this that's a little shorter:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:74
msgid ""
"If you'd like to have a different default per-directory, that's easy too! If "
"you run this inside of a project:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:81
msgid "Or, if you'd like to target a different version of Rust:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:86
msgid ""
"Then when you're in that directory, any invocations of `rustc` or `cargo` "
"will use that toolchain. To share this with others, you can create a `rust-"
"toolchain` file with the contents of a toolchain, and check it into source "
"control. Now, when someone clones your project, they'll get the right "
"version without needing to `override set` themselves."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:92
msgid "Installing other targets"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:94
msgid ""
"Rust supports cross-compiling to other targets, and Rustup can help you "
"manage them. For example, to use MUSL:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:101
msgid "And then you can"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:107
msgid "To see the full list of targets you can install:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:113
msgid "Installing components"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:115
msgid ""
"Components are used to install certain kinds of tools. While `cargo-install` "
"has you covered for most tools, some tools need deep integration into the "
"compiler. Rustup knows exactly what version of the compiler you're using, "
"and so it's got just the information that these tools need."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:120
msgid ""
"Components are per-toolchain, so if you want them to be available to more "
"than one toolchain, you'll need to install them multiple times. In the "
"following examples, add a `--toolchain` flag, set to the toolchain you want "
"to install for, `nightly` for example. Without this flag, it will install "
"the component for the default toolchain."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:126
msgid "To see the full list of components you can install:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:132
msgid ""
"Next, let's talk about some popular components and when you might want to "
"install them."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:135
msgid "`rust-docs`, for local documentation"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:137
msgid ""
"This first component is installed by default when you install a toolchain. "
"It contains a copy of Rust's documentation, so that you can read it offline."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:140
msgid ""
"This component cannot be removed for now; if that's of interest, please "
"comment on [this issue](https://github.com/rust-lang/rustup.rs/issues/998)."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:144
msgid "`rust-src` for a copy of Rust's source code"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:146
msgid ""
"The `rust-src` component can give you a local copy of Rust's source code. "
"Why might you need this? Well, autocompletion tools like Racer use this "
"information to know more about the functions you're trying to call."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:154
msgid "`rustfmt` for automatic code formatting"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:156
msgid ""
"![Minimum Rust version: 1.24](https://img.shields.io/badge/"
"Minimum%20Rust%20Version-1.24-brightgreen.svg)"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:158
msgid ""
"If you'd like to have your code automatically formatted, you can install "
"this component:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:165
msgid ""
"This will install two tools, `rustfmt` and `cargo-fmt`, that will reformat "
"your code for you! For example:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:172
msgid "will reformat your entire Cargo project."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:174
msgid "`rls` for IDE integration"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:176
msgid ""
"![Minimum Rust version: 1.21](https://img.shields.io/badge/"
"Minimum%20Rust%20Version-1.21-brightgreen.svg)"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:178
msgid ""
"Many IDE features are built off of the [`langserver` protocol](http://"
"langserver.org/). To gain support for Rust with these IDEs, you'll need to "
"install the Rust language sever, aka the \"RLS\":"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:186
msgid ""
"For more information about integrating this into your IDE, see the [RLS "
"documentation](https://github.com/rust-lang/rls)."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:189
msgid "`clippy` for more lints"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:191
msgid ""
"For even more lints to help you write Rust code, you can install `clippy`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:197
msgid "This will install `cargo-clippy` for you:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:203
msgid ""
"For more, check out [clippy's documentation](https://github.com/rust-lang/"
"rust-clippy)."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:206
msgid "The \"preview\" components"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:208
msgid ""
"There are several components in a \"preview\" stage. These components "
"currently have `-preview` in their name, and this indicates that they're not "
"quite 100% ready for general consumption yet. Please try them out and give "
"us feedback, but know that they do not follow Rust's stability guarantees, "
"and are still actively changing, possibly in backwards-incompatible ways."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:214
msgid "`llvm-tools-preview` for using extra LLVM tools"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustup-for-managing-rust-versions.md:216
msgid ""
"If you'd like to use the `lld` linker, or other tools like `llvm-objdump` or "
"`llvm-objcopy`, you can install this component:"
msgstr ""

